Topsham Dec. 13th, 1846
Dear Mother,

    I received your excellent and most welcome letter yesterday.  I had been expecting a letter for a good while, in fact had got entirely out of patience of waiting, and three or four days before had written again to Milo, which it seems however you had not received when you wrote.  It must have been not far off though.  It seems you had quite a Thanksgiving at Milo after all.  I did not know whether the boys were going up or not.  I wanted much to go home, probably should if I had not been quite so poorunderlined.  However, now I find I have go to go on to Yale College, it is perhaps better, for now  I can have a vacation.  Next week. I guess I shall start Monday Dec. 21st, and go right on to Yale by Rail Road shortest route, be there Wednesday perhaps Thursday  also and get back the best way I can.  Almeda is in Boston at that time I will make arrangements to stop and call upon her.  I suppose likely the shortest route from Boston
Completed

will be by the way of Worcester and Springfield, & Hartford railroads.  How far would that be from Royalston & thereabouts?  Would it not be a nice plan, if I could only have a fortnight's vacation in stead of a week, and (a much more important "if") if I only had a little money of my own to spend, for me to visit some of the folks there?  You ask why I go to Yale.  It is to be a sort of a Convention, a great meeting of DKE Greek letters from different Institutions.  I am to represent Old Bowdoin there.  It will be a great time,  I assure you.  "A real high old time" as my fellow boarder the "Capting" Merrill would say.  It appears that Lucy is to be at Bangor this winter.  I am really glad of it:  that is if you can get along without her at home.  I think it is just exactly what she needs.  What sort of a chance will she have to get into Society there?  I think she ought to write to me long before this time.  It is long since I have heard a word from her.  She does not write so well as she need to.  I have an idea to go to Royalston & Warwick, but I suppose it will not do.  What sort of a thing is that little penny?  as good as she was last spring?  You know she is a real favorite of mine.  I want you should do really well by her.  Do you not like her better than little James?  I think though that he is a good little fellow; the best of the lot of them.
Completed

It is said that an arrangement has been on is being entered into, by the which this Institution of our Bowd Coll. is to be made a thoroughly Orthodox Orth underlined Institution.  The Board of Trustees & Overseers you know have been partly Unitarians, and the College party under their influence.  This is to be given up.  The Unitarians have agreed to sign off somehow.  The influence of my good friend Mr Wheeler, the U. clergyman to Topeham, the father of my little brother Charley, has been beneficial to that effect.  He says he is satisfied with one Unitarian College in N. E. (Harvard you know) is willing this should be under control of the Orthodox, only let it be liberal and give all denominations a fair chance.  I guess all the Unitarians agree to sign it except old Dr. Nichols of Portland who is rather offish.  The Orthodox on their part agree to get up $50,000.00 for the College within two years, to finish off the Chapel, perhaps endow a new Professorship.  Prof Upham I guess carries it: is very anxious for it: gives $5000.00 himself, perhaps more.  I expect Prof Upham is rather wealthy:  he has made a great deal by his books, is writing all the time, makes one or two thousand dolls. per year copy rights.  This Dec. 16th is our college examination day.  I went on before breakfast & passed firstrate in Astronomy.  let the rest wait till next spring.  I expect I shall feel quite relieved at having no more going to Coll before breakfast.  Next week vacation too.  By the way I had almost a touch of rebellion in my school yesterday.  It is a very bad school, and I
Completed

have before had occasion to threshunderlined a few and even turn out one or two.  Yesterday a case of disobedience underlined etc.  Attempted discipline, and there was resistance, refusal to submit.  I took the chap by the collar, as he raised his fists to defend himself, rapped him a few over head ears & said fists, put my boot? toe against his foot, and let him fall pretty heavily upon the floor once or twice, then put him in his seat, and there he has behaved very decently since. More, while correcting him, half a dozen other chaps, got up & said "That's enoughunderlined"!  Therefore I threshed him a little longer, and then gave them a pretty serious lecture.  There is about the worse set of fellows among them that I ever saw any where.  One of them weighs 214 lbs. too.  However, they are somewhat afraid of me!  I do not know as I shall know where to find Almeda if she is in Boston.  I start Mond 21st. In great haste, just going out to spend evening. Do write to me soon & often. Aff. I. S. M.
Completed

Topsham Dec. 27th, 1846
Dear Mother
It is not long since I wrote to you I believe, only just before my journey, and since I have heard from you:  but I supposed you would like to hear from my adventures; and I should think as you are most all alone, your children gone away, that you would feel sort of lonely and like to receive letters -- just as I do.  So I will write again.  My Journey -- I started by stage Dec 20th Sabbath Eve at 10 1/2 oclock.  (By starting then I could be in Boston 1/2 a day to see Almeda; if I waited till morning, I must go straight underlinedthroughunderlined to get to New Haven in season.  Got to Portland at 3 A.M.  Got into the Cars at 7 1/2 A.M.  Upper Route for Boston, arrived there at 12 1/2 P. M.  Found Almeda & children all well Sissy getting fat again very fast, just been vaccinated &c.  Doctor charged her nothing, only 1.00 vaccination  Going to Sutton soon, waiting for letter from Joseph.  Called with Almeda at Mrs. Child's, and at Mr. Caleb Metcalf's Allen St.  Mr M unwell Rheumatic Fever &c.  Tuesday Rail Road to Worcester, to Springfield, to Hartford, to New Haven, where arrived 4 1/2 P.M.  quite a long ride for one day.
Completed

New Haven is very pleasant place, must be delightful in the summer season; beautiful buildings and abounding in trees, Colleges are a great affair about fourfold of unknown Bowdoin and all so wealthy there too. Societies so wealthy, Hall unknown fitted unknown at? an expense to be reckoned at? thousands,
I staid at New Haven one day &
Completed

What sort of a man is unclear Chase. I did not like his appearance much. I was there at Supper Monday. I do not know as he hardly spoke to me at all. Mrs. Chase seems a very pleasant woman. I concluded Mr. Chase did not want me there if he did unclear. Mrs. Chase invited me to stop there, but I went down to the unclear Hotel, paid one dollar for lodging & breakfast. Rates at New Haven the same. $2,00 per day for board.
I started from Boston 2 1/2 P.M. RailRoad Lower route, by R.R. & Stage arrived at Brunswick Friday night at two or three oclock in the morning, and then slept till near noon, Saturday.
Had quite a journey, pleasant unclear generally somewhat tiresome, unclear so much nights. Expenses in all amounted to some $25,00 or unclear dollars. Part at least unclear will be refunded to me, in the spring.
Found here a letter from Lucy, unclear late news. She seems to be enjoying herself and doing well I should think. Most anxious about your getting along alone.
I dread awfully to go into my school again however, the worst things must have an end.
I do not know as there is any thing in this letter worth sending, but perhaps you will like to hear of my journey. I hope you will write soon and often. Your unclear Son, unclear Metcalf
Almeda is full of plans for getting up a school or a boarding house or something
Completed

Orono Me? March 17th, 1847 Dear Mother, I do not know whether you have heard of my recent whereabouts, or whether this letter may take you entirely by surprise. However, Here I am, at Orono, or as I suppose it is more frequently called Lower? Stillwater, about seven miles from Bangor, comfortably established, boarding at what is called a "verry? nice place", at Dr. Ricker's, and teaching a great "High School." High School, both as being Up Stairs, and as having a high teacher, just from old Bowdoin, and an abundance of high scholars, or those who I suppose think themselves such. I decided to come here last Friday March 12th, just before noon, started at 6 six P.M. by stage, at Portland Augusta, at 12 P.M. till 9 A.M. Saturday. By Mail Stage to Bangor, where I arrived at 8 1/2 P.M. and remained until 4 P.M. Monday March 15th. I can unkown you, or you can well imagine that I wanted to go up? to Milo dreadfully, but could in no manner attain to it, as I was already one day behind my time, and if I remained even a single day longer, should probably have lost the whole concern of my school.
Completed

If I could only have known that I was coming this way, or thought of it a week sooner, I should have started in season to have made a visit to Milo, and been present upon the "Momentous Occasion" as Joseph calls it. Anne, Joseph and Eliab, I found just returned from Milo, I spent part of the Sabbath with Joseph, part with Anne and the night with Eliab, and Monday forenoon in loafing about at Joseph's & Eliab's stores, at Anne's schoolroom, and called at Nat. Harlow's, James P. Veazie's, and Mr Pomroy's. I came up here Monday P.M. and found the people extremely glad to see me, I suppose having feared they had lost their 'Master.' I began school. Tuesday Morning with 44 scholars, in the afternoon 46, and today upwards of 50. I have $3,00 per quarter, $,25 per week, or $1,00 per month for each scholar, My board costs $2,00 per week, other expenses of room, if I have to pay any rent, wood &, probably amount to $,50 per week, all $10,00 per month. So that if I average 40 scholars, I shall clear $30,00 per month, if 50 scholars which seems crossed out at least probable, I should clear $40,00 per month. $100, in two and a half months, which is all the time I intend to remain here, As for security, it is said there is not one not as good & as pure as can be; besides at the last of May, when I shall get through, every man's pocket here is full of Cash
Completed

Orono? April 4th, 1847
Mother,
That word; someone has said, I think it was that noble unclear Lovejoy who was martyred at Alton, Illinois; that word needs no "Dear" before it. unclear all without. 
I received letters from you and Lucy about a week ago; and much good they did me too. It seemed almost an age since I had heard from you. I had heard though to be unclear by the boys at Bangor, whom I saw the day they left Milo, after the wedding. But then, you know, if I could not go to see "Mother & Lucy", I wanted at least to receive letters form them.
However, those letters were exactly what I had been aching for, for two long weeks; and you know that time always seems longer, when one is in a new place, before getting much acquainted; especially if one does not hear at all from former acquaintances; and I had been here almost a fortnight before I hear a single word from Milo, or from my other home & Mother's "Old Boudoir", where I had left many things from which I was anxious to hear from. 
If I thought that Lucy was, or would be @? Bangor, I think I should go down there Last? Day.
Completed

You can hardly imagine how impatient I am to be able to go to Milo; at? first I hardly knew as I should make out to keep up any degree of patience, but I begin to get a good deal interested, and to like my situation very much. I have got one of the very best and very pleasantest schools that ever was seen. I have about forty five scholars, and most of them very good ones, some very forward. About twenty of them are young ladies grown up, and such are altogether the best scholars generally, if one knows how to get along with them just right. They are easiest to govern, that is, if they need any governing; have a much better sense of propriety than young men generally, less of that stubborn independence in wrong unclear them right, which leads young men and their teachers into so much trouble. They are also easier to interest in studies or anything good, though perhaps to be fare, less likely to retain an interest if once excited, but with less to distract the mind. Most of my best unclear are mostly young ladies. Another thing will perhaps amuse you -- my school is closed every day with singing! Pretty well, considering my musical capacities, is it not? The young ladies do it entirely among themselves, and it succeeds finely. Some eight or ten of them, are superior singers, the best part of two or three village choirs. I think it is a fine thing for the school, and pleases the scholars finely. It tends to cultivate and strengthen a good feeling among them.
Completed

It will certainly be extremely convenient for me if Charles can furnish me with some seventy five or one hundred dollars in June or July. That amount at least I must have from some source, in addition to what I shall obtain here; and I rather think, as you say, that I ought to have it from Milo, from the Old Farm. There is certainly property enough there in some shape. It is generally considered that a young man does pretty well, what indeed very few indeed do, if he educates himself liberally by his own exertions, or even mostly; even if he has a few hundred dollars help from some benevolent society. At any rate, it is not generally expected that a young man do more, if his relatives are in any sort of comfortable living circumstances. Now, since I was twenty, or about twenty one years old, I earned one year some more than one hundred dollars in cash, from which I certainly never received anything to help about going to College; and did one about? summer's work, or from Jan. to Sept. and much of the time through summer more work than a common man does or ought to do), on, and about the Old Farm there; before I thought of going to College. Then the year before I entered College, at Foxcroft, in the Academy & Village School, I guess I did as much as pay all my expenses. When I entered College, I had just twenty dollars. Mrs. Childs unclear, have received some unclear from her unclear: besides that extremely little. It is curious how well I have got along: how favorable circumstances & Providence have been. Since entering Coll. I guess I have earned $400, besides keeping my class?
Completed

I suppose likely, in the peculiar circumstances, I hardly know why it should be, but suppose it is so, that it would or will be difficult for Charles, or any body else to furnish me with the money this summer. I suppose too that I could hire the money perhaps. I guess I could find those who would hire it tome. Guess old Frost in Topsham would, perhaps somebody in Bangor would; perhaps the Colburns here in Orono? would; and, if I have my health and strength, and God blesses me as he has done, I could soon earn money and pay it. But, then, I am twenty five years old already; the most valuable portion of my life is fast passing away; and I ought not to be obliged to spend the prime of my strength, physical or intellectual, in some temporary employment to earn money to pay debts!
Still, all that, one way or the other, does not trouble me much. I can earn money any time, or do without. What does trouble me, is -- What shall I do in the world? I ought to have some fixed object in view to lend all my energies towards. What shall it be? You might say the ministry-- but I am not fit for it, and in more respects than one or two; should not be successful in it, in any respect. I think I might be successful as a Physician or Surgeon; that my mind would be fitted for it, unclear. Perhaps. But it is by far the most expensive of all professions, to study as I should want to. I would not be such a Doctor as Dr. Kimball, for instance, I would rather be a day laborer I think. Besides, I might not be able to convince myself sufficiently of the the truths on which the science of medicine is founded in order ever to enjoy myself in it. Then, it would take three or four years of study, and then years -- years -- no one knows how long, before one could be started, enough to establish himself in life; and I am 25!
Completed

I would, for the first thing, throw myself towards the mighty West, into the almost boundless Wisconsin or Iowa, or even across the continent, beyond the eternal bulwork? of the mountains, into the New World of Oregon or California, there to unclear out for myself, in some way, or in some path (in a New World there are always ways & paths enough); a name and an inheritance among the sons of men, a place to employ, for the good of myself and my fellow beings, the "one talent" that my God has given me: I would do this, I say, if it were not, that I like not, myself to separate myself, thus so greatly from those to whom God and nature have bound me by the ties of birth & affection. As Joseph wrote to me once, if Relatives and Friends were given to us as blessings, we ought not, rashly at least, to throw them away, or throw ourselves from them. But in New England prospects are certainly slim, in along? any path of life, for Young Men of Moderate Abilities, not? all the tastes & habits of educated life.
What shall I do -- I cannot well be a Physician; I am not fit for a Minister; I should probably starve to death as a lawyer; and I see no chance of getting an office!
You say you are going to be lonely there after Lucy is gone. Why need you to be? I expect you will fret yourself merely because you do not have every thing to do yourself! Why can not you be contented, after having done your share of Labor, to sit, and look on, and see most anybody else do it, even if they could not do it quite as well as you could? At any rate I wish you would occupy yourself a little more in writing to your children!
Do write frequently.
unclear Son I.I. Metcalfe
Completed

Bond. Coll. July 18th, 1847
Dear Mother,
You can hardly imagine how much I was gratified at receiving yesterday a letter from Milo, I had almost begun to doubt the existence of any such place, or at least of any people dwelling there. I had been in Brunswick six full weeks, and had heard never a word from there, although I had written two or three times I believe. However, perhaps I was glad enough at receiving the letter at last to make up for some of the waiting.  However if it is to be so long before I receive answers to letters, I think I do well to write pretty soon after receiving one.
As for my health, about which you always appear to feel so much anxiety, I have the pleasure of informing you that I never enjoyed better in my life. I am perfectly well, stout, rugged, and healthy, eat like an ox, and sleep accordingly; can tire out my fellows at most any thing, and not worry me; swim three hours per diem, (if I choose), and feel all the better for it.  On the whole, I study some, read more, and get along very comfortably, except when some unlucky circumstance slightly reminds me of pecuniary affairs; but even that, for one as good natured & careless as I am, never lasts a great while.  Did I understand you that you hoped I would have one severe fit of sickness just to teach me to take care of my health?!  I am careful.
Completed

As for what I am to do, or how I am to do it, I am sure I know not. I suppose, if I can get along no other way, I might borrow money enough to get away from Brunswick, leaving my bills all unpaid, of one of the boys; though it might perhaps be some inconvenience to them.  What I am to go to doing I am sure I do not know, & cannot tell or guess. I had about made up my mind, that, now, as I had got my education and begun to be in a situation to be a little independent, that is,k in degree, that I would teach school no more. I really do not like it very well, am not at all inclined to adopt teaching as a profession, or permanent business, and do not think it well to spend time, more than one can help, in any such byplay. Teaching is certainly not of very much benefit as a preparation for any other occupation or mode of life,  Still I may be obliged to teach a little more; if I should go West immediately I should probably have to teach at first.  But I do not want to.  I should like to go upon a RailRoad, to study engineering, think I should be pretty well fitted for that, and stand some chance of succeeding.  But I do not know as there is much chance of my being able to make a beginning, to get into a situation.  I am not
Completed

But it is not very likely perhaps that I can get such a situation right away; There are many who want just such situations. And as long as it is the influence of rich men, R.R. Directors &c. which procures situations for relatives & favorites, rather than real fitness, education, or abilities; I am perhaps not very likely to succeed; at the unclear Rich men's influence happens to be the very article in which I am poorest; more so even than in money, for that I can earn. The other there are two ways in which people possess it. Most who have it, have it by right of birth: that I certainly have not. Some can obtain it by that sort of "faculty for good graces" which some possess, or by "bending the pliant hinges of the knee, where thrift may fallow fawining!" With the first I take it nature has not gifted me; if indeed it be any thing different from the latter, for which I am far too independent to try. 
This day is Sabbath, July 10th, One week from Tuesday, or the 24th I shall get through with Bowdin College.  If I should go home should probably go in the course of that week, in about one week after this letter will reach you. If I can find any thing to do I shall not go home; if I cannot, perhaps I shall, though if I had a little money I thing (sic) I should go to Mass. first.
I have been pulling all the strings I knew how to get hold of, only three or four, to try to get upon a R. Road, immediately.  I had a letter from Uncle Joseph Stevens a short time since I wrote to him about the R.R. business there. He wrote as soon as he got my letter, very kindly, approved my ideas, if he could do any thing for me he would try.  The engineers had left his vicinity, but he was acquainted with some, on other roads &c. He would see some of them &c.
Completed

Warwick, Sept. 10th 1847
Dear Mother, 
I received a letter from you , or rather from Lucy, the morning I left Brunswick, and I believe,wrote something in answer tow it: but, I suppose you would like to hear some account of my doings and unclear unclear, and observations since then. Well, suppose I begin a the beginning, and tell you the whole story. 
Friday morning, Sept 3rd, I left Old Bondoin perhaps for the last time, by stage for Bath $.50 then a ticket for Boston for $1.50,  steamboat unclear to Portland, the Rail Road to Boston, where we arrived at 9 p.m. and I stopped at the Marlboro Hotel, intending to go Sat by R.R. & Stage to Northfield. But by mistake of my Landlord, or rather of his porters, my valise in the morning went the wrong way, and I could not go until too late. However, the gentlemanly Landlord, Mr. Coe, made many apologies, and told me to stop till Monday, free of expense. So I staid, and Saturday, called round to see the people.
Called at Mrs. Childs, her health improving. She has not been very well, her daughters pretty good for her. A Mrs. Reed there, from Winchendon or Winchester of somewhere, from whom they thought you would be interested to hear, though unfortunately seeing so many people & things since, I cannot remember who & what they said, much
Completed

Her Mother I think they said was at Winchester, or somewhere helping house for her, while absent, & I did not think then I should forget so much. I ought to have written before now. Mrs. Reed appeared a very pretty sort of woman. A young Lady, Hannah Tewksbury, I believe, called to see her, used to live with her, quite pretty, attending school at Newton or somewhere Mrs. Child gave me and unclear Pocket Book!
Called on Mrs Chase just returned from the Country not Reyalston though, all well. 
Mr. B.B. Bush died suddenly a week, fortnight ago, went out to Mr. Auburn, complained of feeling ill, returned died instantly, or almost so. I believe I tell the story right. 
I found Cousin Humphrey unclear
Sabbath A.M. Went into the Marlboro Chapel, large, fine Church. Rev. Matthew Hale Smith, of whom you have heard unclear Universalist preached his first sermon before the new so called "Pilgrim Church" House crowded full, say 1000 more. Fine preacher. Text "This is none other than the house of God, the gate of Heaven". P.M. I looked in to half a dozen Churches. Winter Street, Mr. Rogers, crowded full, great quire unclear. Summer St. Trinity Church. Great Aristocratic Episcopal, Splendid house. Once in a while a worshipper a child or a woman occasionally in the great unclear, to hear their pompons service. Same aslo in some of the rich great Unitarian Churches, and at Old South. Near by a Second Advent man roaring away wretched nonsense at an awful rate, to a few inferior looking hearers, hear him though half a dozen streets. 
Evening Park St. Missionary Concert unclear
The Aristocratic are not the Church going
Completed

Monday morning rain. Took the cars for Worcester with Humphrey Stevens who was going on to Albany, as his man Alby had by Telegraphic dispatch requested. He had a great journey, though the Western States last year, 15000 miles 11 1/2 months.
From Worcester by Northfield & Brattleboro Stage to Warmick bu way of Barre Petersham. Of all the enough country that ever I heard of it beats every thing. The road itself not very lively, but more crooked than ten unclear, away round one awful rocky, little hill, then leaping over to just such an then, to mind round to still another in the same way: and soon all day long! Not an acre of land to be seen! but still abundance of farming and orcharding, on little spots of Earth, mashed into hallows among the rocks & ledges. I got out of the stage at a Mr. M. Williams, the nearest point to Warmick village, following a map of "Road to Capt. Joe's" projected upon my note book by H. Stevens Esq. Uncle Joseph not at home, Greenfield. However, they appeared glad to see me. All well. Next day, Tuesday, 7th, I went up to Aunt Conants; staid all day. They are all well. unclear has quite a pretty little wife and two children, and just going next day have now gone, all four, to Barnard, Vermont, to see Samuel. Aunt unclear I think should have known any where, from her resemblance to you. Uncle Conant? complains much of growing old, deafness. He could understand every word I said though. I guess I talk very distinctly. He works as regularly as ever he did. I should guess does exactly as much work. What an awfully "Austere Man" he is to look at ! I guess he is rather good thing.
Completed

4
And Aunt Conant! I cannot begin to tell how good she is. And all is exactly like my Mother, only older. She is, or might have been, a really superior woman, far too much to see here been confined to such a little narrow contracted sphere. Seemed to me just as if no one thing, ever to whip? the doorgard had been moved about there for 16 years! So in the house. So you believe that old wooden unclear had ever been started half an inch from its place? I don't! I did really love Aunt Conany though. And every thing so like my Mother even to cooking and setting the table and washing up the dishes.
Uncle C. I always remember by Deason - at Bangor who looks so much like him, only younger. Hervery. I think looks just as he used, no older.
Wednesday, I started to go over to Unclear Williams. took me a full hour & more to get from Uncle Joseph's to the village. It is positively the most difficult road I ever traveled. So many and so might are the blackberries, that I could not possibly get along. At the village I met Uncle Joseph returning. Knew him instantly. Rather a good looking  Old Fellow. Looks some like a butcher, if he had given up the trade; east, laughing good natured way. I concluded to go back home with him. He bought from over Northfield, Joseph's wife Jane, with her pretty good matured little Eleven months old boy Wells. I do not see as Uncle Joseph had grown old very much, though he just discovered that he is beginning to go bald.
Completed

5
Uncle Joseph is improving much his little rocky pinched? up half bit of a farm. Uses lots of Bog Mud & Ashes, clearing of swamp, holes & everything. Makes it profitable to unclear full of hay. I should think more than in Uncle Conant's tho. Hires a Man and a boy. Unclear Joesphh appears to be a very popular man; and is really a very capable business man, for one of his "Eddication." very well informed. I judge the whole set take them together, here and at Northfield, a very happy family. Wednesday was a rainy day, and Thrusday Morn. Wed. P.M. Came a Mr. Lewis (and wife and daughter) whose son Lenas? is Uncle Joseph's hired man from Winchester?. Mrs. Lewis, who used to be "Bing" or "Viny" or "Livy" Conant, much pleased to know who I was, inquired much after all the folks, sent much love. As by the way do every body many else. All which I do herely deliver. Appears quite a woman just about Charles' age, rather got the start of him thought, I judge by her stout Whiskered son, and the daughter unclear. His Mother (or somebody else) living near here, is sick and like to die; Consumption, I guess. I enquired of her for Josiak K. Metcalf of Royalston said to be teaching School at Winchester. Was so good, and much liked; but then just gone home to attend the funeral of his mother, or rather Step Mother. Next day. Thurs rainy morning, clearer P.M. Funeral of a young man - Abbott, 23 years old. Student, I believe just dies of Consumption. Several deaths likely, among Mr. Hodges, of whose Children Unclear is guardian.
Completed

Thursday P.M. I walked over to Royalston, got there just before or as it began to rain hard. Folks at Uncle Jacob's well, except much worn down by fatigue and grief. Mrs. Metcalf, formerly Mrs Thomas of Winchester, taken sick Wednesday night, Inflamation of the Bowels, or something of the kind, extreme suffering but I believe not thought dangerously until Sabbath night or Monday morning. Died Monday eve. Buried Tuesday P.M. Josiah came home Monday, went back to his School Wednesday. The blow seemed to fall most heavily upon Mrs. Metcalf's daughter, Ms. Nancy S. Thomas by it left as it were entirely alone in the world. Her own father, as well as only Brother and Sister having previously died and not Mother too! When I became acquainted with her, I liked her much. She seemed "cast down, but not destroyed". Very much supported. I judged that she is to be married to Mr. Jos. Walker a well appearing young man, who was there, and with whom I believe Eliab is acquainted, perhaps a correspondence. At any rate I was much pleased with her appearance. 
Uncle Jacob looks old is and shows to be, to have been, and to be still a very hard working man But what a good kind man he is; perfectly ready, and most happy, to do any thing and every thing any personal sacrifice or effort whatever, to oblige, please or benefit, any one. Why there is not one young man or boy in ten thousand hardly, who would jump over a fence now so quick as he would at his age, to gratify any one. How I do love him! I know he is a great deal like my father, in many things.
Completed

Josiah went back to his school Wednesday. Samuel, widower, hires or boards there with his father. Harriet Prescott's Widow, Mrs. Brewster that now is, who lives an Worcester, was up there. I like her very much. Her Oldest, Harlan Peletiah? lives, has always lived, with his Grandfather, a real good little fellow too. 9 years. Prescott Mrs. Brewster bought up with her. In the afternoon, it did not raid. I went with Samuel up to the other place, and up where Father used to live. Every thing seemed to look just as I could remember it, only smaller, narrower, and as if crowded up together, the houses seemed so near, instead of away off as I thought them. I went into the house, the Old Kitchen seemed so little. I suppose I remember it as it seems to me when I used to unclear across its floor, and think it a long ways. Mr. Newton, who lives there has had a stroke of palsy, and cannot speak so as to be understood or hardly more about. The farm I guess is not very well cultivated, or any thing in good repair. They say it is exactly as father left it. No Improvement of course going backward. The farther part of the shed building is all rotted down, looks as if five pounds weight would crumble it. Samuel & I called at Mr. Russell Morse's, Sen. & Jun. My old playmate has two or three stout babies! The Old Man, Samuel said is Rich. We went back across. What a tremendous hill that is. After supper, Samuel carried me over to Mr. Obediah unclear, whose wife Ester, it appears is my Cousin, though I knew nothing of her, or she of me. She has got a pretty little girl though. Her husband it seems is quite a wealthy farmer.
Completed

8
Col. Brown is very sick not expected to live. O. Goddaw? has gone off to try and find his son, Wm, I believe who had gone peddling.
Went to the burying ground
Every body I saw any where knew Capt Issac and was ever so glad to see his son. One rusty Old fellow, Calvin Forbes by name passed me in Uncle's orchard had and exalted remembrance of you, my Mother, for, let me tell you, making him the best mug of punch that ever he drank, when he was once threshing Oats there. How much good that did him! There had not been a week since when he had not thought of it and of you! unclear Chas Rich was the very worst boy that ever he knew any thing about supposed Capt Metcalf would have trained him if any body could but he could do nothing with him. Sent to bring Forbes dinner he would stop to play & sometimes got there before sundown!
Sat morning, I walked back to Warmich expecting to see Cousin Joseph but he not yet return from Boston, and no come Saturday. P.M. in rain went over with Uncle Jos to Mr. Williams, all well. S.E. Balwin Waldron, Yale student, Lucy unclear man there. Lucy appears to be a very fine smart girl, got a grand new piano. Aunt Ester there, does not look six months older or different at all from a dozen years ago. She is going to Barnand Nev to spend the winter. Baldwin & Lucy have just returned from Monadnock? There, if you are not satisfied with news and scramles?. I will give it up. Aff. I.I. Metcalf

Northfield Sept 23d 1847
Dear Mother I believe I wrote to you a very long, though perhaps very careless letter, about a week ago, from Warmick. I write again, not really because I have much to communicate but rather because I am so extremely  desirous anxious to hear something from "Down East" from home; and I do not see much probability of it, if I do not write. It is now more than four weeks since I left Milo and about three since I have heard a single word in any way from Milo or Bangor. When I wrote before I said nothing I believe of whither you could write to me. And I don't know as I am now in fact much more settled unclear then. However, you can direct letters to me her at Northfield, and I am any where in this region, I shall be pretty likely to receive them sometime. I do not now perceive much probability that I shall get away from hereabouts immediately, whether I get a situation on the Rail Road eventually, or not. This is, I do not see as it is likely to be decided right away. So I hope you will write letters to me immediately.
Completed

I think I wrote in my last letter a very prolix? account of all my doings, goings, and seeings, until the 11th unclear. The 11th after returning from Royalston, I went over to Uncle Williams'. The 12th, Sabbath, I herd A.M. Rev. Mr. Clark the new Unitarian Clergiman and P.M. " " Kenney Baptist Clergyman of West Roayalston exchanged with unclear unclear! 12th Monday I came over to Northfield with Cousin Joseph A.S. and have been here much of the time since. Writing - goofing? getting acquainted & sometimes working in the Bark Mill, or doing any thing else I could find. They say that I am sure of employment on this road sometime - The Chief Engineer Edwards, has told me there is no doubt of it. But there great things more slow you know. They have just concluded to go on with a great deal of business this Fall -- when they get ready - And Engineers are Scarce. This Vermont R.R. is to be pressed in unclear only to Brattleboro, but far beyond, up river, Bellows Fall & I don't know where else. And above all that The Directors of this Road, and of Fitchburg, and others have decided to make unclear unclear a great survey for a route from this Road say from Brattleboro, across the Mountains to Troy N.Y.  4 or 5 thousands $ have been already appropriated for the preparatory survey, exploration
Completed

Just how they are all waiting for some formal action of Directors of something or other. I do not know who understands their machinery. But when they do start, maybe tomorrow next week or next month, I expect I am pretty sure of Employment. Last Sabbath A.M. I heard Rev. Mr. Kendall of Barnardston?, exchanged with Mr. Jones, Orthodox Clergyman here. P.M. Rev Mr. Locke of New Salem, exchanged with Mr. Everett Unitarian. Monday 20th P.M. I walked over to Winchester, and went into unclear School of Cousin Josiah K. Metcalf astonished him considerable when I introduced myself after School was over. I guess he is a pretty good school Master, but not likely to be much of ant thing more that that. Stopped there with him Monday night, and returned here, Tuesday A.M. P.M. walked over by and old road through the woods to Uncle Williams' in Warmick. Mr. Baldwin still there. Makes it his home there I should judge. Wednesday a beautiful clear morning went over on Mount Grace with Baldwin. Had a splendid time, the most mountain climbing, I ever met with, and by great odds the noblest prospects I ever say. Baldwin had a very good spyglass. Could see with naked eye Mts Washington, Monadnock, Wachinsett?, Royalyoke & with the glass, Villages to the South & East - many Boryalston, Ashol, Templeton, Petersham, New Salem, Orange, Statesbury, xc, xc. Winchester looks most beautifully, and the valley leading hither? & every thing else in fact. Returned here P.M.

Feb. 23d 1848 Northfield
Dear Mother
After long waiting, and some impatience, I received you letter Monday Eve. 21st insh. I t had got to be about six weeks since I wrote before. It will not do for me to delay writing long after receiving letters from Milo, if I wish to get replies the same season! However, considering the circumstances, and the important events, which have lately transpired, there is some apology for the delay in this last case. I think though that I ought to have been apprised of the great fact a week sooner. Seemed to me I want to see the young gentleman. What will they call his name? Charles? Of course. Couldn't find a better, except it were !Isaac!!! How does Charles ensure his dignity? How I should like to be there to admire his paternity. Why couldn't you tell me how the little fellow looks? Or has in that matter been decided yet?! It is a little curious that Charles should be away in the woods. Rather a great idea to find himself a father so unexpectedly. I do not see how he can go back into the woods again and leave his baby! It is a pity I had not his oxen here if that is all that sends him off. $28.00m per month thought I should think was doing pretty well, all expenses paid; that is, if he gets his pay. Pay "Cash down"? Am much obliged for you account of "relation" I shall rely upon you however to come and introduce me to some of them in the Spring. By the way, Jos. A. Stevens who was at Boston Saturday told me that the oldest son
Completed

of Uncle "Nathan" Stevens , I think it was of Petersham or Barre died the other day: fine boy 12 or 14 of age. Joseph's little boy, I do love a good deal. The poor little fellow is quite sick. was unwell a month or so, got better nicely a week or two, yesterday taken quite sick, they could not bare him to come out to Temperance Celebration. You ask if I have become acquainted with the Barbers. Least week I called on a Mr. Dutton, a very fine man. I  think who said some of his cousins were my cousins, his mother was sister of Mr. Williams of Warwick. His wife is a fine woman. At his house I was introduced to a Miss Barber, quite a pretty lisping young lady. A Mr. Barber I have heard pf as a meanest man, is member of the Church. Rev. Mr. Jones is stating to me the resources of his parish, said that Mr. Barber last 1846 year paid $2.00 for support of preaching. This year 1847 he was so poor he could pay nothing!
You seem to write as if it might be uncertain whether you would come back with me in the Spring! It is just exactly as uncertain as it is whether we both unclear till that time. At any rate I shall not come back without you. And if I should not be able to go Down East in the Spring. Why then you must come. 
As for money, I will have enough for that matter by that time, so do not invent any more excuses. Besides, they ought to be ready to given me free passes over some Railroads by that time.
The fact is, at any rate there is no sort of necessity on propriety in you keeping yourself shut up there at Milo, at the rate you have done for so long.
Completed

Sabbath Evening, March 5th, 1848, Northfield
Dear Mother. I believe I much begin to write again to you and Lucy for it I want after writing once even till I receive your letter; the time becomes so long that I almost forget even writing before "The Stormy March had come at last!" After a winter of almost unexampled mildness, very little snow, no sleighing for a week together any time I believe, hardly any cold weather except a week or two we were out up to Brattleboro; March bids fair to be; at any rate had thus for shown itself, boisterous enough.
Today had been real March weather: changing half a dozen times from bright melting sunshine, to dark gusty snow storms, and a wind that cuts like a knife, raising the snow in clouds, even as it melts under the high Spring Sun.
At the Monthly concert - this afternoon, Dea. Field from another town being present, gave an interesting account of a Revival, lately & now, going on in the town of Heath, west part of this county. A real Revival, like those of other days, which have been so scarce almost unknown for there or four years past. How it does warm ones' thoughts, so that, according to the Psalmist, the fire burns within, to hear again such doing of the Lord. I bought back to my mind the former days, at Brownville in 1842.
Oh that the Lord would again unclear safe to visit his people in Mercy to extend gracious influences of his spirit on every side. How careful too ought Christians to be lest they again excite the displeasure of God as in time past.
The Churches about here, I think must be in extremely bad state; far worse than I know any thing about Down East. Many of them as I hear full of old breaches, divisions, wounds, & some that will not be healed up: often hearing called council after council, and every one leaning matters worse then before. This Church has been in the same way, and that long: difficulties now sleep perhaps only because there is not life enough to show it. As the man who is struck down by apoplexy does not complain of a foul stomach. As I understand from Mr. Jones, there has never been really a revival of Religion in this town! One of the oldest towns too. Mr. Field said that in Heath there have been 10 councils besides References in 10 years.
Completed

There are great times just now among the Irish laborers along the Rail Roads about here. Wages have been this winder &.70 per day for shovellers. That is little enough to be sure considering that they may not be able to work more then 15 or 20 days in a month and their board costs them generally about $2.25 or more per week. But since March came in, and the wages not raised, they have had a general "Strike for higher wages!" all along on this Road and others simultaneously. Not content with stopping work themselves, you see, they undertake to all from working whether they wish or not; marching along the line sometimes three of four hundred together armed with clubs & pick handles, stopping the crews who did not strike, in some instances, destroying cards, shovels, xc. Most of the unclear about here stopped when the rest did, but as yet there have been no overt acts. Some think the mobs will show themselves here within a few days, to break up the crews who are still at work on the bridges xc. No one knows what will be. One of the bridge contractors, who has a crew still at work down on Miller's River, had armed himself with two or three "Revolvers" declaring that no one shall drive his men off the works. He is a resolute fellow too.
I think now I shall continue some way to get off here a week or two the last of April or in May. I rather think they will let me go, if they are not extremely and unclear hurried. I have certainly been very steady at business since I have been here and indeed am in such a situation that they owe it to me. Moreover, those with whom I have to do are the best  sort of men to get along with. Mr. Field my immediate director is a great friend of me, and ready to do any thing to oblige me; and Mr. Johnson, the Chief Engineer, has the reputation of being very obliging in such matters. To be sure, leave of absence for an Engineer is something not usual or to be expected. The universal answer to applications is No. If a Junior ever gets leave of absence it is a special favor. It is a kind or work that cannot stop and no one can take another place for a few days or a week. However, you may fairly expect Me; so of course Mother be ready to come back with me at once. At any rate to come.
Completed

Northfield Sept 2d 1848
Dear Mother,
I was hoping somewhat to hear from some of you by last night's mail, but perhaps you did not get down East in Season, and perhaps if you did you would all be too glad to get home to think of writing to me. So perhaps I better not expect  a letter for a month or so. It is rather curious how defective some of your children are in the art of speech. Some people now can always say just what they wish to, at just the right time. Perhaps it is partly some defect in the brain which does not think of thinks at the right time to say them. Since you went away I keep thinking of things that I really wanted to say, and talk about, to you, & to Lucy, and the rest of you. I began to believe it will not do for me to depend much upon the faculty of speech, as a medium for thoughts; if ever do think of anything I must put it on paper.  
One think I intended to mention to you, that I wish you would speak to Charles about when you get to Milo. You know it has been always allowed that Charles on the place there somehow owed me something. Charles himself said three of four years go that he was going to pay me $100.00 and it was certainly justly my due. I have done more than that worth of hard work these some of it too hard, since I was twenty or twenty one years old. Besides the money that I earned away from home before I went to College more then I ever had any benefit from myself. The fact is I ought to have had those earnings. There was property an
Completed

means enought these for the rest of you: and I needed it for more than any of the rest of the family: One hundred dollars was worth just about a hundred dollars to Charles & the rest of you, sometimes perhaps a little more, possibly $150.00. To me at that time it was work truly worth more than $1000. In fact no money, just the mere property can estimate the benefit of one or two hundred dollars to me just the right time. This Cutting down, "raseeing", a ship builder might call it, a man from "second rate" to "third rate", is not very easily estimated. Yet it is a think very easily done by a little too much of difficulties, or too little of advantages at a critical time. To be sure the man may yet be a very useful man. In some cases indeed he may get clear up again. With a really "first rate", this may be easy enough. When a man had really distinguished himself as a genius, he become a great statesmen, orator, author: they do not stop to enquire whether he got an Oration at College, or indeed whether he has ever seen a college. But with us Common men the case is very different. If the student was not quite high enough for a "Phi Beta-Kappa", nothing he can ever do afterwards will give him an Election and if he does not get higher than a "Common Man's" unclear ought to lead him, then will be apt to remember what he was not, rather what he is. But all this is wandering from the subject; is nothing at all to the purpose. I was going to say that perhaps the matter ought to be decided some how. The fact that I did not have it when I needed it much and ought to have had it, may not prove that I ought not to have it sometimes. I may still need it more than any one else. In a primary point of view I certainly am the poored of the family, and perhaps am likely to remain so; that is in com
Completed

parison with my actual necessities, my needs of money. Now would it not be a good plan for you to mention that matter to Charles find what he feels about it; whether he thinks he owes me any thing, and intends to pay it; and if he does, just get him to send me his note for the sum with interest from some date, back, forward, or present. There appears to be a rather long story, fast; Excuse it, for I may not think of it again, any more than I did when you were here or when I have been at Milo.
What shall I do if I am thrown out of business here, this Fall or Winter and cannot find any other situation? That is the greatest trouble in Engineering; it is not a permanent business and  the getting a situation is perhaps the worst thing about it. Perhaps I was unfortunate in beginning on a road partly finished. The Vt. K. Maso R.R. is now near completion some say it will be finished by Dec 1st at any rate: some say Jan1st, some indeed, next spring. But then that cannot heed so much help at the end you know have been lately turning off some, more will be without doubt before the road is complete. To be sure, they tell me I shall probably be wanted as long as any one; and perhaps I may; as I believe I have made myself pretty useful for my standing & salary: Still I cannot expect always to be favored, even at the expense of those who have friends to book out for them. The Question is, what had I better do? My object of course is to get ahead as fast as possible. Can I do better than to go South, if I can get an opportunity? There I could expect better wages and more rapid advancement; and perhaps full as good opportunity to
Completed

make valuable friends. Perhaps I might like best, even at less wages & pooer prospects, a situation on one of of the Maine Rail Roads; say perhaps Bangor to Waterville: But then I have no influence to push me into a situation to rich or stationed relative, or particular friend, whose influence would help me, or to please whom somebody would take the pains t help me. Most folks now that amount to any thing, except some very few that used to be called geniuses, though the existence of any such animal has somewhat fallen in doubt if these latter times have somebody to help them. Comparatively few really help themselves, as our folds are obliged to, if indeed, they get any help at all. Our family is unfortunately not "connected" if you know what that means.
I might be curious to unclear away round, just how much ever such a man as say Mr. Field here owes to being connected, (and that through rather disreputable channels even of families of drunken paupers) with certain Congress man or Custom House Officers or somebody whose influence would affect something somewhere. This matter of influence is one of the prerequisites of wealth, situation; sometime perhaps talent and being generally less valued than money, is often turned over to "poor relations" & to whom it may be more valuable if possible than to that rich itself. 
There - I have written pretty near four pages of something. Come to read it over, I hardly think I had better try to add any thing to it. It is getting to be rather late to think of writing a letter on this sheet.
